Definition:
Top-level Named Entity types can be used as head concepts for pronouns or other places where you need a simple implicit concept. The most common ones are listed here.
        The teacher ate an apple.
          (e / eat-01
    :ARG0 (p / person
        :ARG0-of (t / teach-01))
    :ARG1 (a / apple)
    :aspect performance
    :modal-strength full-affirmative)

          
        It tasted mealy.
          (t / tast-02
    :ARG1 (t / thing
        :refer-person 3rd
        :refer-number singular)
    :ARG2 (m / mealy)
    :aspect state
    :modal-strength full-affirmative)

          
        My dog came up to me. He said "rwawr".
          (s / say-91
    :ARG0 (a / animal
        :refer-person 3rd
        :refer-number singular)
    :ARG1 (s / string-entity :value "rwawr"
        :quote s)
    :ARG2 (p / person)  *implicit argument, links to 'me'
    :aspect performance
    :modal-strength full-affirmative)

          
        It has no bearing on our work force today .
          (s30s / say-91
    :ARG0 (s30p / person)
    :ARG1 (s30b / bear-06 
        :polarity -
        :ARG1 (s30e / event
            :refer-person 3rd
            :refer-number singular)
        :ARG2 (s30f / force
            :ARG0-of (s30w / work-01)
            :possessor (s30p2 / person
                :refer-person 1st
                :refer-number plural))
        :temporal (s30t / today)
        :aspect state
        :quote s30s))

Other common implicit concepts can come from the names of roles. Some common ones are listed.
         Well it's another Sunday and I'm here at work again!
          (s1a / and
    :op1 (s1h3 / have-temporal-91
        :ARG1 (s1n / now)
        :ARG2 (s1d / date-entity
            :weekday (s1s / sunday)
            :mod (s1a2 / another))
        :aspect state
        :modal-strength full-affirmative)
    :op2 (s1h2 / have-place-91
        :ARG1 (s1p / person
            :refer-person 1st
            :refer-number singular)
        :ARG2 (s1h / here
            :place (s1p2 / place
                :place-of (s1w2 / work-01
                    :ARG0 s1p)))
        :mod (s1a3 / again)
        :aspect state
        :modal-strength full-affirmative))

    
         Average maturity of the funds' investments lengthened by a day to 41 days, the longest since early August, according to Donoghue's.
          (s4s2 / say-91
    :ARG0 (s4c / company :wiki - 
        :name (s4n / name :op1 "Donoghue's"))
    :ARG1 (s4l / lengthen-01
        :ARG1 (s4t4 / temporal
            :duration-of (s4m / mature-01
                :ARG1 (s4t3 / thing
                    :refer-number plural
                    :ARG2-of (s4i / invest-01
                        :ARG0 (s4f / fund)))
                :ARG1-of (s4a2 / average-01)
                :aspect process))
        :ARG2 (s4t / temporal-quantity :quant 1
            :unit (s4d / day))
        :ARG4 (s4t2 / temporal-quantity :quant 41
            :unit (s4d2 / day)
            :ARG1-of (s4h / have-degree-91
                :ARG2 (s4l2 / long-03
                    :ARG1 s4t2)
                :ARG3 (s4m2 / most)
                :ARG5 (s4t5 / temporal
                    :temporal (s4s / since
                        :op1 (s4e2 / early-01
                            :ARG2 (s4d4 / date-entity :month 8))))))
        :aspect performance)
    :aspect state)

        
         The total of 18 deaths from malignant mesothelioma, lung cancer and asbestosis was far higher than expected, the researchers said.
          (s15s / say-01
    :ARG0 (s15p / person
        :ARG0-of (s15r / research-01))
    :ARG1 (s15h2 / have-degree-91
        :ARG1 (s15q / quantity :quant 18
            :ARG2-of (s15h3 / have-quant-91 
                :ARG1 (s15s2 / sum-of 
                    :op1 (s15d / die-01
                        :cause (s15d4 / disease :wiki "Mesothelioma" 
                            :name (s15n / name :op1 "malignant" :op2 "mesothelioma"))
                        :aspect performance)
                    :op2 (s15d5 / die-01
                        :cause (s15d2 / disease :wiki "Lung_cancer" 
                            :name (s15n2 / name :op1 "lung" :op2 "cancer"))
                        :aspect performance)
                    :op3 (s15d6 / die-01
                        :cause (s15d3 / disease :wiki "Asbestosis" 
                            :name (s15n3 / name :op1 "asbestosis"))
                        :aspect performance))))
        :ARG2 (s15h / high-02)
        :ARG3 (s15m / more
            :degree intensifier)
        :ARG4 (s15q2 / quantity
            :ARG1-of (s15e / expect-01
                :ARG0 s15p
                :aspect state))
        :aspect state
        :quote s15s)
    :aspect performance)

Concept takes the place of the unknown argument in WH questions.
         Who put the cookie in the cookie jar?
          (p / put-01
    :mode interrogative
    :ARG0 (u / umr-unknown)
    :ARG1 (c / cookie)
    :ARG2 (j / jar
        :purpose (c2 / cookie  
            :refer-number plural))
    :aspect performance
    :modal-strength neutral-affirmative)

Used for 'whether' or 'if' phrases when they are used to indicate that the truth value of a proposition is not known.
         The man doesn't know whether it's raining.
          (k / know-01
    :ARG0 (m / man)
    :ARG1 (t / truth-value
        :polarity-of (r / rain-01
            :aspect activity
            :modal-strength undefined))
    :aspect state
    :modal-strength neutral-negative)

Used for questions in which a choice is being offered. (Very similar to exclusive-disjunction, but use this for questions.)
         Would you like coffee or tea?
          (l / like-02
    :mode interrogative
    :ARG0 (p / person
        :refer-person 2nd
        :refer-number singular)
    :ARG1 (u / umr-choice
        :op1 (c / coffee)
        :op2 (t / tea))
    :aspect state
    :modal-strength neutral-affirmative)
Used if there is no text in a sentence presented for annotation.

Used if there is no understandable text in a sentence, preventing annotation.
        &&sssffsd**
          (u / umr-unintelligible)

The academic year
          (d / date-entity
    :calendar (y / year 
        :mod (a / academia)))

Definition:
Use for strings that represent sounds or references to text or words themselves (rather than references to the meanings of the text or words).
        Now take the orange blocks and build a =.
          (a / and
    :op1 (t / take-01
        :mode imperative
        :ARG0 (p / person
            :refer-person 2nd
            :refer-number singular)
        :ARG1 (b / block
            :refer-number plural
            :color (o / orange))
        :aspect performance
        :modal-strength partial-affirmative)
    :op2 (b2 / build-01
        :mode imperative
        :ARG0 p
        :ARG1 (t / thing
            :configuration (s / string-entity :value "="))
        :ARG2 b
        :aspect performance
        :modal-strength partial-affirmative))

Refers to all parts within an interval.
        Please read pages 320-325.

    :ARG0 (p / person
        :refer-person 2nd
        :refer-number plural)
